  <!-- FAQ -->
  <div id="faq" class="mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What is operating water in a disc stack centrifuge?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Operating water is the clean water supply used to actuate the self-cleaning sludge discharge mechanism. It serves two functions: pressurizing the sliding bowl bottom to open the bowl and eject accumulated sludge, and maintaining the liquid seal ring inside the bowl during operation. Without correct operating water, the centrifuge cannot perform automatic sludge discharge or maintain liquid seal integrity.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What happens if operating water pressure is too low?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Low operating water pressure causes incomplete or failed sludge discharge — the bowl does not open fully during the ejection cycle, leaving sludge behind. Over time, incomplete ejections cause sludge buildup and bowl clogging. Low pressure can also fail to maintain the liquid seal, causing seal break and process fluid flooding out of the machine.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What water quality is required for centrifuge operating water?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Operating water must be clean, particle-free with hardness below the manufacturer's limit (typically below 200 ppm as CaCO3). Hard water causes scale buildup in operating water passages and solenoid valves. Filtered city water or deionized water is preferred. Never use process fluid or recycled process water — contamination will damage internal water circuit components.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          How do I troubleshoot operating water solenoid valve failure?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Signs of a failed solenoid valve: no sludge discharge despite the timer triggering, operating water continuously flowing (valve stuck open), or no response to the control signal. To diagnose: verify the control signal using a multimeter, manually actuate the valve coil and listen for the click, and check for blocked orifices with a wire or compressed air. Failed solenoid coils and blocked valve bodies are the most common causes.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="border-l-4 border-gold bg-white rounded-r-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="px-5 py-4 font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer hover:bg-gold/5 transition-colors list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          Can operating water be reused in a disc stack centrifuge system?
          <span class="text-gold ml-2">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="px-5 pb-4 text-text text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Yes, used operating water can be reused if the centrifuge is functioning correctly and the discharged water is not contaminated with process fluid. Collect the drain water, allow it to settle or decant it, and verify it is free of oil or contaminants before reuse. In remote locations where fresh water is scarce, a closed-loop operating water recovery system is an effective solution. If operating water is contaminated with oil due to a malfunction, it must be disposed of as oily waste per local regulations.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

